  "prompt": "Which day can be the first and the last day of a century?",
  "response": "A century spans 100 years, and we can analyze dates to determine possible starting and ending days. \n\n1. **First day of a century:**\n   - A century begins on January 1st of the year that is a multiple of 100. For example, the 20th century started on January 1, 1901.\n\n2. **Last day of a century:**\n   - A century ends on December 31st of the year preceding the next multiple of 100. For example, the last day of the 20th century was December 31, 2000.\n\nThe specific day of the week that these dates fall on can be calculated using algorithms or calendar systems that account for the Gregorian calendar rules. Let's look at:\n\n**First day examples:**\n- January 1, 1901 was a Tuesday.\n- January 1, 2001 was a Monday.\n\n**Last day examples:**\n- December 31, 1900 was a Monday.\n- December 31, 2000 was a Sunday.\n\nTherefore, the first and last days of a century can fall on any day of the week depending on the year's configuration while adhering to calendar rules.",
